50|$|Anton de Bary later {{conducted}} {{experiments to}} observe the beliefs of the European farmers regarding {{the relationship between the}} rust and barberry plants, and after successful attempts to connect the basidiospores of the basidia stage to barberry, he also identified that the aeciospores in the aecia stage reinfect the wheat host. Upon de Bary's discovery of all five spore stages and their need for barberry as a host, John Craigie, a Canadian pathologist, identified the function of the <b>spermogonium</b> in 1927.|$|E

